{
  "doc_id": "22207",
  "text": "In Arabidopsis (Arabidopsis thaliana) root cells, a membrane potential in excess of approximately 200 mV and a DpH (proton chemical concentration gradient) of approximately 2 (equivalent to approximately 120 mV) both contribute to the large PMF, which provides the driving force for ion channels like those for potassium and calcium and for secondary symporters transporting amino acids and sugars [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Fig. 1A) . In Arabidopsis, there are 11 plasma membrane proton pump genes, denoted AHA1 to -11 (for Arabidopsis H + -ATPase; [CITATION_4] . Throughout the Arabidopsis life cycle, the plasma membrane PMF is maintained by the two most predominantly expressed isoforms, AHA1 and AHA2, and homozygous T-DNA insertions in both genes create embryonic lethality, indicating a collectively essential function [CITATION_5] . The mRNA expression patterns and protein abundances of AHA1 and AHA2 indicate that, together, these proteins generate up to 80% of the overall ATPase activity in Arabidopsis seedlings and in vegetative tissues of adult plants.",
